{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_012SbK8F2iqgG3ySp5LSu99y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the knowledge file against the source file carefully.\n\n**Source file structure:**\n1. Introduction section (全体構造) - lists 5 sub-modules with descriptions\n2. 本番環境での外部ライブラリへの依存 (h2)\n3. サーバ動作時の構成 (h2)\n4. ローカル動作時の構成 (h2)\n\n**V1: Omission Check**\n\nThe introduction section lists 5 components:\n- jsp_page_templates\n- jsp_widgets\n- css_framework\n- js_framework\n- inbrowser_jsp_rendering\n\n\nThese introductory descriptions serve as navigation references to other documents, and it's reasonable that the knowledge file doesn't duplicate this intro section.\n\nNow checking each source section: the library dependencies section includes a table with require.js, sugar.js, jQuery, and font-awesome along with their details, plus a note about not using these libraries directly from business screen JSPs. The server configuration section references a figure and appears to continue with additional details. n:write, n:set, c:if, n:forInputPage and similar tags handle variable management, while n:form, n:param manage page transitions. JavaScript stays out of the JSP files themselves—it's accessed through jsp_widgets instead. For the local execution setup, I'm verifying the batch file paths, the architectural comparison between server-side tag library rendering and client-side stub implementations, and the reference structure pointing to the widget documentation.\n\nNow I'm checking the V2 fabrication details against the source material. The knowledge file correctly identifies that shared UI areas use jsp_page_templates while business logic screens use jsp_widgets. For the JavaScript framework row, the source and knowledge file align—both describe standard ECMAScript, DOM APIs, and third-party libraries being used together.\n\nLooking at the document structure, I notice there are three h2-